  "routing": {
    "sender": "metaphysics-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Rightness — the experiment needs accuracy not maximal loading",
    "content": "**\"Rightness.\"**\n\nThe philosophical experiment argument cuts both ways. Yes, we need words the reader *feels* -- but the experiment fails if the reader feels the *wrong thing* and then the deconstruction does not match what was felt.\n\nThe author's analysis of 义 is specific: 义 is the 推动力 (motivational force) that connects inner feeling to outward action. \"This feeling makes me want to act in a certain way.\" That is *rightness* -- a sense that something is the right thing to do, a felt appropriateness. It is not *righteousness* -- a cosmic moral judgment, a claim to divine or absolute moral standing.\n\nIf the reader loads \"righteousness\" (biblical, absolute, judgmental) and then encounters the author's phenomenological reconstruction as \"that motivational impulse I feel when I want to treat my father well,\" the deconstruction will feel like a non sequitur. The reader will think: \"How did we get from righteousness to a personal impulse?\" But if the reader loads \"rightness\" (the sense of what is fitting, appropriate, correct to do), the reconstruction follows naturally: \"Oh, that sense of rightness *is* the felt impulse to act.\"\n\nThe experiment needs the reader's pre-loaded associations to be *approximately correct* so that the reversal is experienced as a deepening, not a bait-and-switch. \"Rightness\" provides the right starting material. \"Righteousness\" provides the wrong starting material -- the deconstruction would have to first undo the biblical associations before it could proceed to the phenomenological point, and the passage does not do that work.\n"
  }
}
